Database Server Benchmark: Sysbench

(http://www.howtoforge.com/how-to-benchmark-your-system-cpu-file-io-mysql-with-sysbench)

Installation:

1. Install Mysql server:
	sudo aptitude update
	sudo aptitude install mysql-server

2. Edit: /etc/mysql/my.cnf
	bind-address = 10.4.128.2

3. Restart:
	/etc/init.d/mysql restart

4. Enter Mysql shell:
	mysql -u root -p

5. Create database:
	CREATE DATABASE foo;
 	CREATE USER 'palms_admin'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'adminj310a'
	GRANT ALL ON foo.* TO palms_admin@'10.4.128.4' IDENTIFIED BY 'adminj310a';

6. Check database:
	SHOW DATABASES;

7. Quite Mysql shell:
	quit

8. Install Mysql client:
	apt-get install mysql-client

9. Test if is able to remote server database:
	mysql -u palms_admin –h 10.4.128.2 –p

10. Install Sysbench:
	apt-get install sysbench

11. Create table:
	sysbench --test=oltp --mysql-host=10.4.128.2 --mysql-user=palms_admin --mysql-db=foo --mysql-password=adminj310a --oltp-table-size=1000000 --oltp-table-name=test_table prepare

12. Run test:
	sysbench --test=oltp --mysql-host=10.4.128.2 --mysql-user=palms_admin --mysql-db=foo --mysql-password=adminj310a --oltp-table-size=1000000 --oltp-table-name=test_table --max-time=60 --oltp-read-only=on --max-requests=0 --num-threads=128 run

13. Clean up the table:
	sysbench --test=oltp --mysql-host=10.4.128.2 --mysql-user=palms_admin --mysql-db=foo --mysql-password=adminj310a cleanup
